http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Physical Education is an integral part of the total education of every child from kindergarten through grade 12. Therefore, every student should have the opportunity to participate in a quality physical education program. It is the role of quality physical education programs to help students develop health-related fitness, physical competence in movement activities, cognitive understanding, and positive attitudes toward physical activity so that they can adopt healthy and physically active lifestyles. Quality programs are also important because they provide learning experiences that meet a student's developmental needs, which in turn helps to improve the mental alertness, academic performance, readiness, and enthusiasm for learning.

Uses a pedometer to record 10,000 steps daily.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identifies places in the community where the activities and sports learned in class can be played and enjoyed.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Identifies parks, bike trails, pathways, and other available means for achieving and maintaining an active lifestyle.
Joins a community youth soccer league.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Achieves and maintains a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Seventh grade students should be able to participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity in a variety of settings. They participate in physical activities addressing each component of health-related fitness while focusing on cardio respiratory endurance. They assess their personal fitness status for each component and use this information to assist in the development of individualized physical fitness goals with little help from the teacher. They will use this information to develop a plan to improve or maintain cardio respiratory fitness. They can assess their own heart rate, breathing rate perceived exertion, and recovery rate during and following physical activity

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Uses results from a criterion-referenced fitness assessment (e.g. Fitnessgram) to monitor improvement.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Completes a cardio respiratory, flexibility, and muscular fitness assessment from the criterion-referenced test.
Compares their scores from a fitness assessment to healthy standards provided by the teacher and targets areas needing improvement.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: With teacher assistance, student develops a plan for improving cardio- respiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Sets realistic personal goals for improving cardio-respiratory endurance based on their fitness scores.
Develops a training program that will lead to safe participation in a day long hike.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assesses physiological indicators of exercise during and after physical activity designed to improve or maintain cardiorespiratory endurance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Keeps a record of heart rate before, during, and after vigorous physical activity.
Engages in physical activity at the target heart rate for a minimum of 20 minutes.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Exhibits responsible personal and social behavior that respects self and others in physical activity settings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students recognize the role of physical activity in respecting diversity and continue to include and support each other, respecting the limitations and strengths of group members. They have well-developed cooperation skills and are able to accomplish group/team goals in both cooperative and competitive activities.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates cooperation with peers of different gender, race, ethnicity, and/or ability in a physical activity setting.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Seeks out, participates with, and shows respect for peers with differences in ability during a small-sided game.
Applies sensitivity to the rights and feelings of others to resolve interpersonal conflict during physical activity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Remains on task without close supervision.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Practices task during allotted time.
Self officiates a badminton game.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Values physical activity for health, enjoyment, challenge, self expression, and/or social-interaction.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students recognize and appreciate the intrinsic values of developing higher physical skills as a means for promoting self-esteem and self-expression as well as physical health. Self confidence is gained through participation in new challenging activities that decreases personal insecurity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participates in health enhancing activities for personal challenge.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Participates regularly in physical activity to meet personal goals.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Willingly tries new activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Joins a team or tries a new activity for personal enjoyment.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students will demonstrate the ability to use mature forms for the basic skills and tactics in six of the eight categories listed below by the end of grade 8 using activities that have been taught during sixth and seventh grades as well as the activities suggested for eighth grade. The following activities are suggested for eighth grade:

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performs specialized manipulative skills in an applied setting to include dribbling and passing.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Dribbles a ball during speedball while preventing an opponent from stealing the ball.
Performs a bounce pass during a small-sided basketball game to get the ball around an opponent.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performs movement skills in complex activity settings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Places the ball away from opponent during a rally in a net game and returns to ready position.
Creates a step aerobics routine combining a variety of movement patterns.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates use of tactics in small-sided games.

Chooses the appropriate club for strokes of varied distances during a golf unit.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates understanding of movement concepts, principles, strategies, and tactics as they apply to the learning and performance of physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students exhibit an increasingly complex discipline-specific knowledge of biomechanics and movement skills. They understand and apply movement concepts/principles and game strategies, critical elements of activity-specific movement skills and characteristics representing highly skilled performance. Students know when, why, and how to use strategies and tactics within game play.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identifies movement and strategies necessary for skilled physical performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Diagrams expected ball rebound angles for three different shots in racquetball. Explains a strategy for advancing a runner in softball.
Describes the biomechanical reason for stepping in opposition when throwing overhand.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identifies key critical elements of complex motor skills.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains the critical element necessary to execute a successful cross in soccer.
Lists three factors that contribute to a slice in a golf swing.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes an athlete's performance of a sports skill and provide suggestions for improving the performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Observes a team of elite volleyball players during game play and describes the movement skills that enable success in serving, passing, and spiking.
Identifies errors in the performance of a golf swing and suggests appropriate changes.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identifies and applies principles of practice and conditioning to enhance performance.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Describes conditioning concepts that will allow one to play for longer periods of time without fatigue.
Practices the volleyball forearm pass in a stable or closed environment (e.g. against a wall or with a partner toss).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Applies appropriate tactics and procedures to various movement forms.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains proper procedure to lead or follow a partner while dancing.

They make independent decisions about their physical activities that enhance their lifelong health. They meet healthy guidelines by participating regularly in moderate to vigorous physical activities both in school and outside of school settings.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participates daily for 60 minutes in physical activity of their choosing.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Generates a list of activities that can be done at home which leads to a healthy lifestyle.
Goes canoeing with friends.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identifies ways to increase levels of physical activity in daily routines.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Helps build bike paths/fitness trails assessable to meet the needs of students with special needs.
Walks the stairs instead of taking the elevator.
Participates in activity based video games that require movement. (i.e. Wii fit game, Dance Revolution).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Achieves and maintains a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Eighth grade students participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity on a regular basis without undue fatigue. They participate in physical activities that address each component of health-related fitness, including muscular strength and endurance, flexibility, and cardio respiratory endurance. They can self-assess their personal fitness status for each component. Students are introduced to the various principles of training (e.g., threshold, overload, specificity) and how these can be utilized in improving personal fitness. At this level, students should be able to interpret the results of physical fitness assessments and use this information to assist in the development of individualized physical fitness goals. They will use this information to develop a plan to improve or maintain muscular strength and endurance.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Interprets results of criterion-referenced fitness assessments and develops a plan for reaching fitness goals.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Uses dynabands to increase upper body strength.
Develops a set of exercises using own body weight to increase strength.
Develops an individualized physical activity program using results from fitness assessments, personal interests, and available resources.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Applies basic principles of training to design and implement a program for maintaining or improving health-related muscular strength.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Writes and implements a circuit weight training program designed to meet physical fitness goals.
Applies threshold, overload, and specificity principles to create a plan to improve muscular fitness.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participates in muscular endurance activities for a sustained period of time.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Participates continuously in a muscular endurance circuit for 30 minutes.
Participates in an invasion game or aerobic dance class for 30 continuous minutes.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates the ability to resolve conflicts in a physical activity setting.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Handles conflict with others without confrontation during a disagreement in a volleyball game.
Officiates games during sport education units.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Assumes leadership roles to facilitate class management.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Helps prepare activity area for class.
Suggests ways to improve class safety.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students realize their personal interests and are encouraged to participate accordingly to maximize the benefits of physical activities. (They participate in physical activities for challenge, social interaction and group membership, as well as opportunities for continued personal growth in physical skills in their applied setting).

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Recognizes the role of sport, games, and dance in modern culture.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Attends an athletic event at a nearby college or university (e.g. basketball, volleyball, gymnastics).
Demonstrates an understanding of the ways sport and dance influence American culture.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze the relationship between inactivity and obesity and diabetes type II.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Describe the impact of inactivity and weight gain.
Describe the relationship between inactivity and the onset of diabetes type II.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Appreciates the aesthetic performance of self and others.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Uses activity for self expression and writes a reflective essay about the beauty of athletic performance.
Describes the benefits of a variety of activities.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates competency in motor skills and movement patterns needed to perform a variety of physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students in grades 9 – 12 will demonstrate the ability to participate in a variety of invasion, net/wall, field, target, individual, outdoor, fitness activities, rhythms, and dance. Students will demonstrate competence in at least one activity from two of three following categories: Category 1: invasion, net/wall, or field games; Category 2: target, dance/rhythm, or outdoor activities; Category 3: fitness or individual activity. The following activities are suggested for grades 9-12:

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates competence while performing skills in a variety of settings or activities including sport, rhythms, and other lifetime and recreational activities.

Executes a dance, rhythmic, or gymnastics sequence in the context of a routine.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Performs skills, which at a level of competency, contributes to health related fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Dribbles, runs, passes, and shoots the ball in team handball with a basic level of competence.
Performs a gymnastics routine that demonstrates strength and flexibility.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates understanding of movement concepts, principles, strategies, and tactics as they apply to the learning and performance of physical activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students will increase their motor skill level by utilizing principles and concepts connected with movement and examination of skills. Students will perform in movement patterns and psychomotor skills associated with physical activities. Students will explain tactical decisions and their appropriate use in various sports/activity settings.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Integrates a variety of strategies, tactics, concepts, and skills during sports and activities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students are able to transition from an offensive position into a defensive position in a game if basketball.
Knows when to use a drop, lob, or drive shot to score in a game of badminton.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Creates a sequence of movements (dance, gymnastics, sports, etc.) that transition and flow smoothly from one to the next.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: The goal of this standard is to connect the skills and activities that are learned in physical education class to the lives of students outside the classroom. Participation outside of class is critical to developing active and healthy lifestyles and behaviors. Emphasis is placed on developing self-management skills and voluntary participation in areas of interest that are meaningful to the student. Students make a personal commitment to participate in moderate to vigorous physical activity in order to maintain personal fitness goals. Students are knowledgeable of appropriate training principles and understand how to apply these to enhance their participation and desired level of fitness.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Utilizes effective time management skills to incorporate opportunities for physical activity outside of physical education class.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Creates a daily calendar of physical activities to ensure participation in health enhancing activities.
Keeps a fitness journal recording detailed workout information (i.e. number of sets, repetitions, types of lifts, distances) in school and non-school settings.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participates in school or community based physical activities with little or no cost.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Participates in school intramurals or club activities that involve physical activity.
Identifies local walking trails or parks and goes walking with friends.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Achieves and maintains a health-enhancing level of physical fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students will assume individual responsibility in their personal behaviors. Students will understand and develop higher levels of basic fitness and physical competence needed in a variety of activities for school and non-school settings, including, home, workplace, and community. To maintain a healthy lifestyle, the student will demonstrate the ability to assess, evaluate, implement, and adjust a personal fitness plan that includes proper nutrition and a disease awareness that reflects ever-changing individual needs throughout life. Achievement of this standard will encourage participation necessary to support and sustain good health.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Implements a comprehensive fitness plan and adjusts various components of fitness necessary to maintain a healthy level of fitness throughout life.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Applies specificity, overload, and progression to increase the intensity of the work out.
Modifies fitness plans due to life changes such as age or injury. (e.g. a team sport activity to an aquatics activity due to an injury.)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Maintains or improves fitness level by using the results of the national fitness assessment to guide changes in a personal program of physical activity.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Increases the number of repetitions in a weight training workout to increase muscular strength.

Participates in lifetime fitness activities (from different sections of the activity chart) at the appropriate heart rate level for 30-60 minutes per day 3-5 times per week in both school and non-school settings.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Uses technologies to assess, enhance, and maintain health-related and skill-related fitness.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Uses tools such as heart rate monitors and pedometers during exercise.
Uses the internet to obtain reliable resources to develop a healthy lifestyle.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes the relationship between physical activity and longevity.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates the relationship of exercise (fitness) and nutrition.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Exhibits responsible personal and social behavior that respects self and others in physical activity settings.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Students exhibit responsible personal and social behavior that respects self and others in physical activity settings, while understanding the role of sport and physical activity in a diverse society. http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Displays the ability to design rules, procedures, and routines appropriate for the group.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Demonstrates the ability to apply the rules and etiquette of various physical activities regardless of societal or cultural differences.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Applies safe practices in the physical education setting.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Wears safe and appropriate clothing to participate in physical activity.

They strive to improve and refine their skills through practice and participation in their selected activities. They experience feelings of satisfaction when they improve their level of performance and meet personal goals. As a result, students will begin to actively pursue lifelong physical activities that meet their own needs.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Explain(s) why participation in activities is enjoyable and desirable either alone or in a group.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Participates in activities designed to improve skills for personal challenge, enjoyment, and expression.

Creates and records a self-generated list of reasons for choosing to participate in selected physical activities in an activity log.
